					<p>Taken from the RUFORUM website:<a href="http://www.ruforum.org/category/documents-taxonomy/ruforum-monthly-newsletters" target="_blank">http://www.ruforum.org/category/documents-taxonomy/ruforum-monthly-newsletters</a>&quot;&quot;Professor Elnour K. Abusabah, the Vice Chancellor of University of Gezira signed on behalf of the University of Gezira a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the Ministry of Agriculture and Natural Resources, Gezira State for sugar beet cultivation and processing settlement. According to the agreement the university will spare 10 hectares from its farm to accommodate a pilot plant to process 50 tons per day of beet. The main objective of the plant is to train farmers and technologists in cultivation and processing of sugar beet by taking advantage of the research being conducted by the Sugar Institute of the University of Gezira. Sugar beet is largely a temperate crop with some cultivars found to be adapted to tropical and subtropical climate.In 1959 the Sudan government prioritized sugarcane cultivation for sugar production. The use of sugar beet is a supplementary effort to produce sugar from beet where Pakistan, Morocco, Egypt and other countries are adapting the concept. In 1992 Syngenta introduced the concept of tropical sugar beet and later in 1998 an extensive trial work started in all the sugar schemes. The conclusion was that sugar beet could be grown in Sudan successfully to obtain sugar yields similar or better than those produced by sugarcane with the advantage of using 30 % of the water and the land. Being a member of the family of Chenopodiaceous, sugar beet can tolerate high salinity and alkalinity. The Sugar Institute is the first body to be involved in extensive cultivation and processing of tropical sugar beet. Research on aspects of optimization of water requirements, crop improvement, agronomic traits( including weed control) and crop protection is on-going.</p>
